ce:section.ce:para:
The N-CPDs were synthesized by l-histidine and ethylene imine polymer via a simple one-step hydrothermal method (Fig. 1
                        ). The N-CPDs are spherical nanoparticles with an average size of 9.88 ± 0.42 nm and good mono-dispersity (Fig. 2
                        a). No lattice stripes of N-CPDs could be observed, revealing that N-CPDs are typical of carbon polymer dots [33]. As illustrated in Fig. 2c, the surface status information of N-CPDs were observed on FT-IR spectra. The strong peak at 3415 cm−1 was attributed to the stretching vibration peak of NH and OH, respectively [34]. The characteristic peaks of 1654 and 1550 cm−1 belong to the stretching vibration of CC and the stretching vibration of CN, respectively [35]. The peak at 1450 cm−1 is because of the bending vibration of NH, and the characteristic peaks at 1045 cm−1 are attributed to the stretching vibration of CO bond [36]. The UV–vis absorption spectra of the N-CPDs is displayed in Fig. 2d. N-CPDs have three UV absorption peaks at 225 nm, 300 nm and 356 nm, and the most dominant absorption peaks are at 300 nm and 356 nm from the π → π* transition of CC bond and the n → π* transition of CN bond, respectively [37]. The fluorescence spectra of N-CPDs are presented in Fig. 2e, which shows the maximum excitation wavelength at 440 nm and the maximum emission wavelength at 530 nm, respectively. There is a certain excitation dependence phenomenon [38]. Subsequent experiments were conducted using the maximum emission wavelength of 530 nm to test the fluorescence performance of the samples. The surface functional groups of N-CPDs were further analyzed by XPS. From Fig. 2f, the XPS full scan spectrum shows three main peaks at 290.2 eV, 403.5 eV and 529.9 eV belong to the binding energies of C 1 s, N 1 s and O 1 s, respectively. The high-resolution C 1 s spectrum (Fig. 2g) contains three major peaks from the CC/CC (284.88 eV), the CN (285.88 eV) and the CO (288.48 eV) [39]. The high-resolution O 1 s spectrum (Fig. 2h) can be deconvoluted into two peaks at 531.28 eV and 533.18 eV, corresponding to CO and CO, respectively [40]. In the high-resolution N1s spectrum (Fig. 2i), 395.28 eV and 396.08 eV were derived from Pyridinic N and Pyrrolic N, respectively [41]. Once again, it is proved that the surface of N-CPD is rich in multifunctional groups, which can bind well with metal ions and form chelates.
